1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,610
The second thing I'd recommend is that you read Dr. Schindler's great book,

2
00:00:04,719 --> 00:00:08,050
How to Live 365 Days a Year.

3
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:16,769
Dr. Schindler shows in this book that three out of every four hospital beds are occupied by people who have EII,

4
00:00:17,039 --> 00:00:19,250
Emotionally Induced Illness.

5
00:00:19,760 --> 00:00:27,170
Imagine, three out of four people who are sick right now would be well if they learned how to handle their emotions.

6
00:00:27,359 --> 00:00:32,610
Read Dr. Schindler's book and develop your program for emotions management.

7
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:36,930
Third, I'd resolve to live until I die.

8
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:47,329
I went on to explain to this troubled fellow some sound advice I received many years ago from a lawyer friend who had an arrested case of tuberculosis.

9
00:00:47,599 --> 00:00:54,130
This friend knew he would have to live a regulated life, but this hasn't stopped him from practicing law,

10
00:00:54,159 --> 00:00:57,490
rearing a fine family, and really enjoying life.

11
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,969
My friend, who now is seventy-eight years old, expresses his philosophy in these words.

12
00:01:04,479 --> 00:01:10,130
I'm going to live until I die, and I'm not going to get life and death confused.

13
00:01:10,479 --> 00:01:13,250
While I'm on this earth, I'm going to live.

14
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:15,409
Why be only half alive?

15
00:01:15,599 --> 00:01:22,769
Every minute a person spends worrying about dying is just one minute that fellow might as well have been dead.

16
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:28,370
I had to leave at that point, because I had to be on a certain plane for Detroit.

17
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:33,329
On the plane, the second but much more pleasant experience occurred.

18
00:01:33,599 --> 00:01:37,250
After the noise of the take-off, I heard a ticking sound.

19
00:01:37,599 --> 00:01:44,290
Rather startled, I glanced at the fellow sitting beside me, for the sound seemed to be coming from him.

20
00:01:44,800 --> 00:01:48,850
He smiled a big smile and said, Oh, it's not a bomb.

21
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:50,370
It's just my heart.

22
00:01:50,959 --> 00:01:55,890
I was obviously surprised, so he proceeded to tell me what had happened.

23
00:01:56,399 --> 00:02:03,649
Just twenty-one days before, he had undergone an operation that involved putting a plastic valve into his heart.

24
00:02:03,839 --> 00:02:11,649
The ticking sound, he explained, would continue for several months, until new tissue had grown over the artificial valve.

25
00:02:11,919 --> 00:02:14,209
I asked him what he was going to do.

26
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:18,050
Oh, he said, I've got big plans.

27
00:02:18,159 --> 00:02:21,329
I'm going to study law when I get back to Minnesota.

28
00:02:21,440 --> 00:02:23,730
Someday I hope to be in government work.

29
00:02:23,920 --> 00:02:27,250
The doctors tell me I must take it easy for a few months,

30
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:29,649
but after that I'll be like new.

31
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:33,649
There you have two ways of meeting health problems.

32
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:38,769
The first fellow, not even sure he had anything organically wrong with him,

33
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:46,130
was worried, depressed, on the road to defeat, wanting somebody to second his motion that he couldn't go forward.

34
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:54,130
The second individual, after undergoing one of the most difficult of operations, was optimistic, eager to do something.

35
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:58,049
The difference lay in how they thought toward health.

36
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:02,850
I've had some very direct experience with health excusitis.

